{{Quote|Do not call our servants technology. We serve the gods, and other living things serve us.|Tsavong Lah|<ref name="The New Jedi Order: Edge of Victory I: Conquest">''[[The New Jedi Order: Edge of Victory I: Conquest]]''</ref>}}
'''Biot''' was the phrase the [[Yuuzhan Vong]] used when referring to their biotechnology.

==Overview==
The Yuuzhan Vong insisted that their technology not be referred to as such, since technology had mechanical connotations for them. One example of these living servants of the [[Yuuzhan Vong empire]] were the '''divination biots''' used by the [[Priest caste]] and their seers who used these creatures as a means of determining the future under the dictates of their religion.

====Qreph Brother Biots====
The Qreph brothers, [[Marvid Qreph|Marvid]] and [[Craitheus Qreph|Craitheus]], at some point learned the technique to manufacture their own biots. Unlike the Yuuzhan Vong's biots, the brothers' biots had biological flesh and organs grown around inorganic [[vanalloy]] skeletons. They manufactured at least three generations of biots from their [[Base Prime|hidden base]] on the surface of a mysterious monolith in the [[Chiloon Rift/Legends|Chiloon Rift]]. From this base they were experimenting in the creation of [[Force-sensitive/Legends|Force-sensitive]] biots by attempting to make copies of [[Ohali Soroc]] and [[Leia Organa Solo/Legends|Leia Organa Solo]]. However, these biots were mostly unsuccessful and it was theorized that their unnatural creation contributed to their inability to successfully tap into the Force without severe mental handicaps or physical deformities. The [[Nargon]]s were also a product of the Qreph's biot research, as was [[Lando Calrissian/Legends|Lando Calrissian's]] operations chief of [[Sarnus Refinery]], [[Dena Yus]].

==Behind the scenes==
The term "biot" was originally coined by [[Wikipedia:Arthur C. Clarke|Arthur C. Clarke]] in his [[1972]] novel [[Wikipedia:Rendezvous with Rama|''Rendezvous with Rama'']], as a [[Wikipedia:portmanteau|portmanteau]] meaning "biological robot." The biots reappeared in the sequels two decades later, [[Wikipedia:Rama II (novel)|''Rama II'']], [[Wikipedia:The Garden of Rama|''The Garden of Rama'']], and [[Wikipedia:Rama Revealed|''Rama Revealed'']], as well as the [[Wikipedia:RAMA|''Rama'' computer game]].

